segments.text: I remember Uncle Jesse and we were going down the trail.
He said, you know, Little Ava, you're old enough that you should be learning poetry.
I'm going back when we get to the house and find my poem book, and I'm going to teach you a little poem about the flowers.
I think that every little boy and girl should learn poetry when they're little.
They'll appreciate it.
Well, I didn't know what the word appreciate meant, so I asked him.
But, of course, I didn't say appreciate.
I said, appreciate.
So he explained it to me.
And when we got home, he found the... Look at us going from that one guy that we always go from door to door.
We were just going to be able to just pause on them and pull apart their dick and take them.
Uncle Jesse found his poem book and it was a long poem.
I looked back several times in my childhood and wondered how in the world he took the patience and the time to teach me such a long poem.
But I will recite as much of it as I can remember of it for you.
The buttercups are coming and the scarlet columbines, and in the sunny meadows the dandelions shine.
And just as many flowers as your soft hands can hold, the little ones may gather, all fair and white and gold.
Here blows the warm red clover, here peeps the violet blue.
Oh happy little children, God made them all for you.
The little birds fly over and oh how sweet they sing to tell the happy children that once again it's spring.
The gray, green grass comes creeping so soft beneath their feet.
The frogs begin to ripple, a music clearing sweet.
To me, that is a beautiful little poem.
I have forgotten the last two verses, but that's been many, many years ago.
Well, I...

remember as we went on up there and he'd teach me that poem i'd have to learn a verse every day and then he took time out to show me uh the different types of little birds that flew over from this poem and he'd show me the birds nest and how they built them and he'd let me hear their call and then i had to learn a poem a

about the birds and it was i know a secret just we three robin and i in the sweet cherry tree but robin knows it best because he built the little oh i can't tell the rest oh i'm afraid i'll tell you every minute but if the birdies in the tree don't feed
I'll try my best the secret to keep.
Now that one wasn't years so long, but I want you to know that it was the hardest words to say secret.
And it was just a hard job for me to say those.
I was tongue-tied when I was little.
And my mother often laughed and said, I believe they clipped it at both ends.
You just chatter all the time now.
Well,
That's one of those things that mothers get disgusted with little tutors right under their feet.
My goodness, my mother had three of us right under her feet all at the same time, you might say.
But that was a great experience.
And you know, I look back and he taught me my first poem.
Well, I don't know.
I believe and I firmly believe that what is planted in children's mind when they're from one to seven is the making of their life as far as principle, love, and consideration of their fellow man.
Now, I'm a strong believer in that, and I want you to know that Uncle Jesse didn't lay anything aside.
He had a wonderful philosophy of life.
However, he did have a temper.
Well, I don't know a fellow worth a tinker's do that doesn't have one, just a little anyway.
But I look back, and I had to learn speeches when I was little.
Well, I had to learn to speak and get up.
at Christmas time and say speeches to get my presents.
So I guess it hasn't hurt me any.
Well that was learn to say speeches when I was little and learn to ride horseback or ride I guess anything.
I can remember Uncle Jesse putting me on the back of old Dink and that was an old milk cow, an old Jersey milk cow, raw boned as she could be and he put me up and let me ride her from the gate.

up to the capian lot of an afternoon and of course that just thrilled me to death i'd have a bouquet of flowers for my mother in one hand and i'd be right i'm just setting up on the old dink if she'd have spoofed at anything i don't want to happen i guess flowers and me and uncle jesse's been scattered all up and down that trail because him with that wooden leg he didn't have wasn't too stable i wouldn't imagine
As time went on, I remember my mother telling me, calling me one afternoon and said, Little Ava, don't you think that you could take your daddy a little bit of water up in the field?
I know the water that he has is hot, and you could carry him up there, couldn't you?
And I looked at her and I said, But the sticker's a bad mother.
And she said,
Yes, I know they're bad, but they'll be worse if your daddy doesn't have some water and can plow that corn because we won't have any cornbread for next year if we don't take care of it.
Well, I don't know.
That kind of stuck with me a lot of times, I thought.
Now, if you don't do this, well, you're not going to have it next year.
My mother laid a foundation of preparedness all the way through life for us children in more ways than one.
That's just a simple illustration.
She was always looking out for tomorrow to take care of her little brood.

Anyway, I put on some shoes, and because the sand burrs were so bad and the bull nettles, and I went up and took my daddy some cool water, and it just thrilled him, and he just thought that was the grandest thing, that I'd walk up to the end of the turning row and bring him a cool drink of water.
He was great to brag on his children when they did something, and of course we would
I think that was great.
I'm afraid in everyday life today we forget to pat our little folks on their back and tell them how proud we are of them.
You know, just a spoonful of sugar makes the medicine go down a lot of times.
I only wish that I could recall the many, many times that my daddy has bragged on me when I know I didn't do it.
bang-up job, but he wanted me to feel like that I had done well.
He was pleased.
So after all, if you can please mother and daddy and please yourself, what else matters?
It wasn't long until we moved back to Johnson City and my little sister Margaret was born out at Flat Creek.
what we called the Steveson Place.
And again, I couldn't say Steveson.
I'd say the Teefy Place.
And I did love Grandma and Grandpa Steveson so dearly.
And again, there I was introduced to music.
They always had Edgar and would play the jugs, washboard, or anything.
Just made up a band of all the things that he could play right there in the old saw.
And they had a regular band of their own, and we'd go over, and I'd be there.
Grandma used to make the best homemade ice cream if anybody ever walked.
And we'd have ice cream on Saturday night, and music, and sing.
My mother and daddy both could sing so pretty together, and they'd all sing.
For some reason, there never was a Sunday that ever went by as long as we lived on the part of Malice River.
We didn't gather at Grandpa Johnson's and have singing.
And his bunch of boys and girls could really sing, and he had a beautiful voice.
And they'd play the piano and sing.
And we moved down to Johnson City.
Well, we missed going to Grandpa's on Sunday and singing.
But we'd go over to Stevenson's and sing and have just as much fun.
Not near as much fun, but we'd have a lot of fun.
Then we stayed down at the Stevenson place the whole year.
And Margaret was born on the 4th of May.
Then in the fall, we moved back up to Stonewall.
And Papa bought a part of Clarence Martin's place, which was Uncle Clarence.
Bought 280 acres from him and 160 from Grandpa Johnson and 160 from Willem Pesa that was our neighbor to the north of us.
and margaret and i were little things and my daddy was farming and he had a team of oxen and old tom and ned and tom was the sweetest old steer that you ever saw and
I'd go up into the field.
My daddy would put me up on his back, and I'd get to ride home on old Tom.
Oh, and that was more fun to get to ride.
Tom was just as kind.
But Ned wasn't.
He wouldn't dare let you ride him.
And my daddy would tell me, now, if you've got to be good to Tom, and you've got to shuck corn for him, and you've got to get his cottonseed ready, because if you don't, he won't walk.
you to ride his back.

You can imagine how little I was, but I'd shuck that corn, and I'll guarantee you I'd pack that cotton seed in that gallon bucket just as tight as I could get it so Tom would have all that he could eat that night in order that I could ride, get a chance to ride him again the next day.
Well, that was one more way of promoting a kid into doing its work and doing it
But that is just a wet philosophy of hanging kids, which is a good thing to me in lots of restaurants.
My father had these two steers that he had decided that he, oxen rather, they were, well, they were steers, but they were oxen, that he wasn't going to try to use them any longer.
He'd already gotten his land all broken.
They were not very good at using in the rows.
It was good to turn the land under, but when it came to the row crops, they were just not the best in the world.
They were good, but not as good as he thought the little mules would be.
So he bought a span of mules called Frank and Charlie after the two Stevenson boys were such good friends of his that we lived on down here on Flag Creek.
And that's what he used then to lay his cotton by.
I am sure that I was over four years old that summer, and my daddy fixed a little old.
Well, it's a flower sack for me to pick cotton in.
just work like a little turk getting that flour sack full of cotton.
And my grandpa Johnson would brag on me and what a fine girl I was to help my daddy.
And I'd come in and wash my hands and I'd always set the table for my mother.
That was my job as a little bitty thing.
And I'd set the table for her for every meal.
And I can remember
When we would sit down at the table, lots of times I'd be so tired and so hungry that I'd almost fall asleep after I got still.
But my daddy, if it wasn't anything but God bless his food and our family.
Amen.
It was something that he was grateful for.

at that time and we knew as little folks that we should bow our little head and then as time went on my mother taught me to say grace and my little sister and we took it turns about saying grace of a morning at the table something
that I feel like that carries over into adult years and age.
And I am grateful for the many, many things that my parents gave me in early childhood that I will remember.
My father had rheumatic fever, or I say rheumatic fever, it was sciatic rheumatism, not rheumatic fever.
sciatic rheumatism, and the doctor thought it was from riding our cultivator seat and bruising that sciatic nerve.
Well, we sold out and we moved down and bought a place on the Perlin Allis again, down on the river from Louie Danz.
In other words, we just swapped places with him.
And of course, Louie had a lot more
land than we did, but it wasn't tillable soil like ours was a stone bowl.
But we moved down there, which is about two miles from my grandmother Chapman, about a mile from my Aunt Ola and Uncle Buddy Chapman.
And we'd have to ride to school, and that was about six miles to school, horseback.
But my goodness life, I had been riding everything
since I could remember almost.
And Grandpa Johnson bought me an old pony when I wasn't but two years old and a saddle.
And the old pony's name was Old Cousy.
And my saddle was a little old Mexican.
It had a great big old horn like a Mexican saddle.
And he picked it up somewhere and brought it to me.
And I'd go down.
I'd ride down to his house, go across that river, get his mail over on the other side at the Lutheran Church, and bring it back.
He'd see me coming.
He was sitting on that porch, and he'd say, ha, ha, ha, you're riding old koozie.
And that just tickled me to death.
Grandpa would laugh and
and asked me if I was riding the old coosie.
Of course, it just thrilled me, and I couldn't get her out of a snail's gate.
If you'd fall off of her, she'd just stand there and wait until you got her to get back on.
But she's always so tall, I always had to lead her up to a gate to get on her, climb up on the gate, and then on to her because I couldn't reach the stirrup bus a little.
But it wasn't any trouble, I'll assure you, to ride, because I learned that from the cradle on.
We came up here to Johnson City to school, and that was just like, oh, it was a foreign country in more ways than one.
The people along Pearl and Alice up there, one big family.
They were German folks and I learned to talk German.
I could talk German about as well as I could English or maybe better.
I could think faster in German than I could in English.
And I came down here and I didn't mix at all good with them because they all didn't anybody talk German.
Of course I butchered it up like it was pitiful the way I butcher up my English with the German.

lots of times i didn't get well i just didn't get anything done at school and my daddy and mother would have to come in and see what was wrong well it was just a language handicap that was all it was a barrier and i think that's one of the things when i was teaching school i had such a feeling for the children who had that language barrier
And I helped them, and I guess I went over backwards towards helping them to get straightened out, more so than I did the others that were less fortunate in the work.
But it was a great experience, and I enjoyed going to school, and I'd go by.

and something go wrong i'd stop and tell my grandma chapman and man she'd call up my mother and she'd say now those little things i they stopped by here and i gave them something deep now you dress up the children warmer it's going to be cold tomorrow now you be sure and send them a slicker oh i'll tell you she gave orders
My mother would have to follow that.
Grandfather Johnson and Grandmother Johnson on the other end.
I'll tell you, I don't know how my mother and dad ever got along as well as they did with us because we were the oldest of the Klan Johnson kids and the oldest of the Chapmans.
And I'll tell you, they both were after my mother and father all the time.
Well, those kids are gonna get killed.
You let them ride, you let them do anything.
My poor old mother, bless her heart, she'd walk out every morning to see us off on those horses.
And she said, girls, don't ride so fast.
Now take your time.
You've got plenty of time to get to school.
And be careful.
My mother would go back in the house to finish her work.
My daddy would be at the gate.
And he'd reach over and cut a peach tree.
and switch, and he'd say, here, girls, use it on those old horses and put the button to them and get there so you can play if you want to.
Now, that wasn't exactly right, but I can remember him doing it, and it just tickled us dead.
We'd wait every morning for him to cut us a switch to get those old horses going.
Well, we made it through those years.

it's a it's a wonder i've had a lot of great experiences for instance mr at the hyatts lived across the river from us and there wasn't a woodsman in the world that was as great as sid hyatt i don't guess he knew all about the animals how they borrowed why they hid their their
their young in the manner they did.
He absolutely studied and knew wildlife and nature from every angle.
And it was such a pleasure to ride the pasture with him and he'd tell you all about it and he'd show you.
It was wonderful.
I'm just wondering if you ever, ever
watched a mother coon and her babies when she would take them down to the river and teach them to fish.
I'll tell you, that is one of the most fascinating things that a little person ever watched in their life.
I don't know how Uncle Sid ever kept me quiet long enough that I could watch it all, but I did.
And I can remember it.
That was the cutest thing that I ever hoped to see in my life.
And I wish it were possible that every child could see a mother coon teaching her babies to fish and how she'd do it.
It was just as much like a human being teaching her child.
And you'd hear her just chatter and chatter to those little babies on the bank.
And she'd catch them in that fur and she'd shake them.
She'd just shake them good whenever they didn't do what she told them to do.
And one was a bad one and it reminded me of myself, I guess.
It was always a first to try something and it went down to try and she turned around and she grabbed that little fella and she shook him good.
I forgot all about the most important thing that happened.
when I lived up at Stonewall before I moved down to Johnson City the second time.
Grandfather gave me this old mare called old Cousy when I was two years old in this little saddle.
And I was so proud of it.
And I would go by and pick Lennon up and ask him if he wanted to go down right across the river with me and get the mail.
And every time that we'd go over there to get the mail, he always wanted to ride in front of the saddle and do the guiding.
And I'd let him because it was easier to say, yes, you can do it than it was to fuss and battle with him.
And I'd always lose anyway, so I'd give up and let him ride in front because I'd have plenty of fun riding her home.
And all I wanted to ride, and he didn't get to ride.
His mother never let him.
And if she'd catch us before we got off, she wouldn't let him go then.
She's always afraid something happened to him.
But he went with me that day.
And we went to take Grandpa Johnson's mail to him, and then went back down to his house.
We got up there where Grandpa was.
Grandpa sat down.
He told us to get down.
He had us something there.
And got down off our horse and gave him his mail, and he had us some peppermint candy.
And we sat down, and he began to talk to us.
And he told Lyndon that
He should always ride behind.
Little ladies needed to ride in the saddle, and they needed to keep their clothes clean.
To be a nice man and polite and kind, he should ride behind me.
Lennon said, well, I don't ever get to be the front rider, and I want to be up front sometime.
Grandfather talked to him a long time and finally convinced him that it was his place to ride behind.
Grandpa told him, said, now as long as you live, Lennon, you're going to know that little Ava is your big sister and you're going to have to listen to what she tells you.
You're going to have to be good to her.
Now children, remember that you mustn't take sides against one another.
Be sure you know that you're on the right side and stand by one another because nobody else is going to take up for you like your own flesh and blood.
And there's not but one thing I can tell you.
And he got up and he stretched his body
run his hands through his beard, and he said, just remember this, kids, that blood runs deeper than water, and you can't turn against your own flesh and blood, regardless of what they do in life.
If you don't stand by them, who is?
Think about it.
Don't get mad at your little sister now, Lennon, and get on and
Ride like a little man.
Well, we got on, and we went on down to Aunt Rebecca's, and she gave us a lecture about going off without telling her.
So over the time that we got around the back of the house, Linda says, I'm going to tell you something, little Ava.
If I'm going to have to ride behind, we're going to fatten this old mare up.
We're going to put some flesh on her bones, because I'm not going to ride behind here.
These old bones sticking through, they hurt.
I said, well, how are we going to do it?
He said, well, can you unsaddle her?
And I said, yes, I can unsaddle her, but I can't get that saddle back on her when I get ready to go home.
He said, well, we won't worry about that.
Pablo will be here in a little bit.
That was a Mexican boy that worked for Uncle Sam.
He said, Pablo will be in to milk the cow a little bit.
And I said, we'll get him to saddle her.
Well, that sold the deal with me, and I wanted to play a little while with Lennon anyway, so we unsaddled her.
We got a wash tub and went to the oak bench.
And we filled that thing up about half full of oats and put it out there.
We were going to get her good and fat.
And she ate until she couldn't eat.
Then she drank some water, and we never could get the saddle on her, of course.
She found her.
She died that night.
But I did get the saddle, get the masseuse to put the saddle on her.
And by that time, she'd already begun to swell.
So when I got ready to go home, there wasn't any use in trying to,
to saddle it up.
I just sat up on that saddle just like it was girded up tight on her, but it wasn't.
Went home next morning when I went out to the barn, my old koozie was laying dead in the hammer and the thing.
Linda and I fattened her up overnight.
That was another thing that, boy, it stays with me forever.
I couldn't hardly stand the idea of taking old Cousy off and letting the buzzards eat her.
And that was something else that Uncle Jesse did.
He took me down, and he said, did you ever see a buzzard dance?
Well, I said, no, no.
How does he do that?
Do they have partners?
He said, I'll take you down and show you.
We went down to where old Cousy was.
And those old buzzards would hop all around and how they'd run up and grab and run back.
And it was a buzzard dance, all right.
It was something to behold.
And that was another experience that I'll donate to Uncle Jesse for being pretty good about teaching you the where's and wherefores of life with nature.
As long as I can remember, when it came Christmas time, we always went up to Uncle Clarence Martin's, what is now the Texas White House, and that's where we would have our Christmas.
The inside of this living room, where the Christmas tree was always placed,
is a huge fireplace that burns four-foot wood.
It has a hearth that is built up 17 inches from the floor.
And we would stand up on this hearth for our stage to say our speeches or sing our songs or to do our dance, whatever.
And then we were given our present from the Christmas tree after everyone had finished performing.
And Uncle Clarence would always see that we had all the fruit and candy and cookies that we could take care of for the day.
He was always great to have his own pups, and he was a great hunter.
And we loved dogs, and we thought how much fun
would be to get out and play with them.
He'd let us turn them loose and play and they'd run and we would run with them and they'd bark and oh it was just a lot of fun.
We thought how much fun it would be to ten can them.
So we put the dogs back in the dog run which was the side of the fence there.
We caught one at a time and we had ten cans and
rolled up paper bags and were tied to their tails and whatnot, turned them loose.
And Uncle Clarence came out, and he saw that, and he called us all in and set us down.
And we had court on this fireplace hearth, and we were all up in front of it.
And, of course, he was the judge.
He talked to us about how bad that we had acted, that how good he'd been to us for this Christmas, how wonderful he thought it'd be.
And then we went out and tinned Candy's dog.
Well, it was more than...

five minutes till we were all in tears and begging to to forgive us and ask him to please give us another chance that we would never do him that way again and he made us promise that we wouldn't to fulfill that he suggested that we all bring in so many loads of wood and put there by the fireplace to use well we were punished all right
and by having to do that work.
Then when it was time to eat our lunch that day at dinner time, as a usual thing, he always fixed a great long table for all of us to eat by.
But he postponed that a little bit that day, and all the grown folks ate and got through.
Well, he had the

made to come in and clear the table and put us a plate down he came in told us now that this is another thing that he had done he prepared a wonderful meal for us and hoping that his little dogs would at least get the bones but he wasn't about to trust us to go out there to feed him but no telling what we'd do to him
And he didn't know whether he'd ever be able to trust us again or not.
Well, that started the music all over again.
And we told him how sorry we were and we wouldn't do it again.
So we ate our dinner.
We got through.
And, of course, we were more anxious than ever to get the bones to the dogs.
We took them out there and brought our plates back in.
When we came back in, well, he said, well, he was going up to Stonewall, but didn't suppose that we'd want to go.
We'd rather stay there and tend Candy's dogs.
Well, we finally got him to let us go.
In place of going to Stonewall, we went on up to Fredericksburg.
And we had a nice evening out.
We came back in.
Our parents were waiting for us.
Uncle Clarence said, oh, well, that's all right, you folks.
Just go on home.
Leave the children here with me.
Because they'll have a good early start in the morning, and they'll have a dog apiece, the tin can.
Well, we didn't live that down for a long time, I'll guarantee you, but we learned our lesson right fast.
He was a very persistent judge, and he had great reasoning ability, and he really had a way with kids.
Made a big impression on our lives, I would say that, for Uncle Clarence.
He never made a better man, a better Christian man.
He was really a wonderful person.
And we look forward every year to going to the big house for our Christmas.
I can't ever remember going to Grandfather Johnson's when Uncle Clarence was living, because we'd go up there.
That's the way he wanted it.
That's the way it was.
Whenever it was threshing time in the spring of the year,
My mother would always go down and help paint Frank with the threshing, and then she in turn would help my mother up at our place.
This year, my mother made chili in a big wash pot.
I'll never forget that.
I thought, my goodness alive, so much chili.
But nevertheless, it was all eaten because all of the hands came around from
They would bring theirs from the joining fields there at Clarence Martin's in Thrash.
And they had beans and chili, homemade light bread, coffee.
And I can't remember the type of cake.
All I remember is it was a cake.
I didn't care very much for cake as a kid unless it had a lot of filling on it.
And sure enough, this didn't, so I didn't pay much attention to that.
And they had all kinds of salads, green salads and fresh vegetables from the garden.
In other words, it was a feast to behold when freshening time came.
And everybody pitched in and helped.
All the neighbors would come and bring food at noon and help with everything.
That is when, that was when living was real living and man, a friend and
Indeed, a need was a friend indeed, and they all gathered at that time.
Petty jealousies and things didn't exist.
If they did, they were set aside when it comes to things like that because everyone flew in and helped their neighbor, and they got along like one big family.
It was a wonderful thing to grow up in a community that had that much community spirit and love.
I cherish those memories because that implanted in me one of the greatest things that life could have, unselfishness.
And in that little community, you didn't find it.
Everybody loved and wanted to help.
If you wanted to build a barn, they'd come in and help you.
You didn't have to go hire somebody to help you.
They helped you do it.
There's always someone who was a good partner that would always come out and help.
My daddy helped haul the lumber that built the first school there, the Little Junction School, where Lena and I went to school.
Do you think that they paid people to build that?
No.
All the community went together, and they built that little schoolhouse.
Now that shows community spirit.
That shows love for their children.
and to show you that there was no animosity toward their church or toward this strife of religious colored creed or whatnot.
In the summertime, the minister
of the Lutheran Church would conduct a little, well, much like your Head Start program for all little folks that had never been to school, and he would start them right there.
And whether you were a little Mexican boy or a little Mexican girl, well, we didn't have any colored folks working there, but always lots of Mexicans.
We went to school with them, and they loved it.

this minister's name is best I can remember Reverend Heinrich and he was one of the sweetest if you say men are sweet you say they're kind and they're gentle well he certainly was and he took so much pains with us in trying to put forth in everyday life what it meant to be good to our fellow man and to love one another
I don't think that anyone could be brought up in an atmosphere of love any more than we were and to love our fellow man.
And Grandpa Johnson used to say to us, you speak.
It never cost you a penny to smile and say good morning, but it may cost you a lot not to sometime.
It's always best to be happy and be grateful for what you have.
It could be that you wouldn't have anything, and then you would have something to grumble about.
But whoever you meet in the morning, you speak.
Be sure you do that.
I can remember that, and I was just a little bitty treat.
And that's one of the traits that has followed me all through life.
Be friendly and speak to your fellow man.
It never costs a penny to smile and say good morning.
You know, that's a pretty good philosophy when you stop to think about it.
It pays dividends.
As we would look back on our little school, we had double desks in this little school.
And your partner was supposed to always be older than you were and take care of you.
In other words, it was a big sister and little sister game, a big brother and little brother.
And I think that is a pretty good idea.
And there were eight grades in this little school.
The older students would help the younger ones with their work, and we enjoyed it.
And then we would read to one another, and we would spell and do our numbers.
I know for sure and certain, without a doubt, that we got a better foundation
In our work.
Then then we have today.
Because I'm a teacher and I know from where I speak.
When I was in the first grade, came to Johnson City.
I want you to know Miss Florence Walker was my first teacher here.
We had to know every one of our multiplication tables.
And we knew him.
Don't think we didn't.
And we had to know how to read.
and spell, and we didn't go anywhere.
We were retained until we did get the basics.
I don't know.
They say, who fails?
Is it the teacher or is it the child?
Well, that is a $64 question.
Who does fail?
It takes two people to make a failure.
Now, remember, it takes two.
